In 2012, I had the honor of visiting the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (@livermore_lab). Ten years later, they have succeeded in achieving groundbreaking for the future of our planet. The scientists there successfully reproduced the power of the sun in a lab. 

This is the first fusion reaction in a laboratory setting that actually produced more energy than it took to start the reaction.

Why you should care? Glad you asked. If this could be done on a large-scale, it would offer an energy source without pollution and greenhouse gases. Clean energy at its finest. This is why I’m excited and hopeful for the future of our 🌍.

Subject: Gratitude for 44 Enlightening Trips Around the Sun and Remembering Mom (Purple Angel 💜)🌞

As I celebrate my 44th completed journey around the sun, I'm filled with profound gratitude for the wealth of knowledge I've gained throughout the years. Life has been a never-ending adventure of learning, and I'm humbled by the vast expanse of wisdom that still awaits me.

Today, however, also brings a bittersweet reminder of the loss of our beloved mother two years ago. Some may say we lost her too early, but I believe it was exactly what was meant to be. Not a day goes by without thinking of her, praying for her, and missing her deeply. Although my birthday no longer begins with her loving call at 12:00am, I still celebrate her life daily, cherishing her memory and the lessons she taught me.

As morbid as this may sound, I say it with a positive outlook and love for life: one more year passing means one more year closer to seeing her again. She remains an integral part of my life's tapestry, and her love continues to guide and inspire me.

With each passing year, I'm reminded of how much there is to discover, explore, and understand. This sense of wonder has not only deepened my appreciation for life but has also inspired me to become a more attentive listener and an eager student of the world.

As I embark on the next phase of my journey, I look forward to embracing the role of a lifelong learner with open arms. I'm excited to continue listening, growing, and evolving, and I'm grateful for the opportunity to share this adventure with all of you.

Thank you for being a part of my life and for contributing to the incredible tapestry of knowledge and love I've been so fortunate to weave together over these 44 orbits. Here's to a future filled with even more growth, understanding, and connection.

With heartfelt gratitude 🙏🏼

I’m a huge proponent for utilizing nuclear energy as a truly sustainable source of energy, which might sound surprising at first, but I truly believe it’s the best solution for the renewable (or sustainable or clean) energy “crisis” many parts of the world is facing (especially Europe). 

That is why it’s so disheartening to see that Germany has just closed their last nuclear power plant earlier this month 🤦🏻‍♂️. 

The reliance on zeroing out fossil fuels isn’t going to happen anytime soon (my bet, isn’t going anywhere in my lifetime) so closing Nuclear plants to pursue renewables is dumb. 

Energy prices have been surging, and closing nuclear plants is just dumb now, especially for a country with close to ZERO natural disasters. Utilize fossil fuel to slowly wean our way off of them is the right approach or else you’ll end up with skyrocketing energy prices and the first people to get hurt by it are the poor communities. 

Talking about nuclear energy and the good it can do for our planet is important to combat the current narrative.

As always, I’m curious to hear everyone’s opinions.

It’s Space Week! 🚀🌎🌠

Space Week is a global celebration of space science and technology, and their contribution to the betterment of the human condition. It is held every year from October 4th to 10th, and it is the largest space-themed event in the world. 

Each year, Space Week has a different theme that reflects the current trends and challenges in the space sector. This year, the theme is “Space and Entrepreneurship”, which are two of my favorite things. 😂

During Space Week, hundreds of events are organized across the globe by various groups and individuals, such as schools, museums, universities, companies, and space agencies. These events aim to educate and inspire people of all ages about the wonders and benefits of space exploration and innovation.

Don’t forget to look up at the sky and marvel at the beauty and mystery of our universe. 🌌
Can the future ever truly be animal-free? Unfortunately I don’t think that will ever happen, and here’s why. Let me know what you think in the comments.

Hundreds of thousands of whales and dolphins die every single year by ending up as bycatch.
Wherever there is fishing, there is bycatch—the incidental capture of non-target species such as dolphins, whales, marine turtles, and seabirds. Once they've been caught, they are simply discarded and thrown back overboard dead or dying. 

Future Oceans is an incredible company we are pleased to support in its mission to protect and prevent these beautiful animals from ending up as bycatch through their innovative pingers.

A concept I’ve been learning about is the butterfly effect, which is a part of chaos theory. It teaches us that even in small, specific systems, it's really hard to make accurate predictions.

Imagine it like this: if you make a tiny change in the beginning, it can cause a big difference in how things turn out later in complex situations. Also, many systems have something called feedback loops, which means that when those small changes get into the system, it's tough to predict what will happen next, and it can create unexpected consequences.
